As smartphones compete for bandwidth with everything from smart-home sensors to autonomous vehicles, we will need new wireless technologies—badly.
True 5G coverage will require new wireless infrastructure including new routers like these Verizon mini-towers as well as new devices.
5G relies in part on short-frequency millimeter-wave wireless to send huge amounts of data over small distances. Small antennas mean receiver chips, center and left, can be built into tiny devices.
One of the first routers announced to support Wi-Fi 6, the TP-Link Archer AX11000, looks like an alien spaceship; the antennas help connect your devices.
Netgear’s Nighthawk AX12 is another spaceship-looking router that supports Wi-Fi 6. It is backward-compatible with existing bands of Wi-Fi, so you could safely buy one now.

Rather than connect to the internet, Bluetooth’s role is to connect devices to each other. The Apple Watch Series 4 uses the newest version of Bluetooth to sync with your iPhone, without draining both batteries.

Could a similar selection of just 80 plays, about half as many as what is typically listed on some of today’s play sheets, work in the modern game?

“It’s not about plays, it’s about execution,” Parcells said. “Sometimes people do better with more. I was always someone who tried to do better with less.”

Patriots offensive coordinator Josh McDaniels, who calls the plays for New England, operates a version of the same offense, designed by Ron Erhardt and Ray Perkins, that Parcells deployed with the Giants and later with the Jets when Bill Belichick was his defensive coordinator. It’s one designed to reduce the number of plays. So it isn’t a surprise that McDaniels is also a “less is more” guy.

“You’ve got to be careful with going overboard and doing too many things that are unfamiliar to your players,” McDaniels said in a conference call earlier this season. “The most important thing is that [the players] know what to do and can do it at a high level.”
